subSubSection.paragraph:
Both ilia are preserved (
Fig. 19
). The right has suffered considerable erosive damage with most of the ventral border including both peduncles missing. Furthermore, some of the medial surface and the posterior postacetabular process has been eroded, as has the tip of the preacetabular process. However, what is preserved of this bone appears to be free from major distortion, apart from some possible slight transverse compression. The left ilium is more complete and forms the basis for much of this description. Its preacetabular process has been crushed transversely in its most distal section and the very tip of the preacetabular process is also missing. The posterodorsal section of the postacetabular process has been lost to post-mortem fracture and erosion, and the distal end of the pubic peduncle is damaged by erosion.

Only the right femur is preserved (
Fig. 22
). There are deeply excavated areas proximally that have affected the femoral head, greater trochanter and the dorsal surface of the anterior trochanter, while much of the distal end of the femur, including the condyles, is missing. Other than these eroded areas the bone surface is generally well preserved although is there crushing to the diaphysis posteriorly.
